{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567811"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19447"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19447"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.03,0.02,0.81,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89993"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12174"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74152"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4236"},{"type":"tags","id":"4267"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34948"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89993"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-centimetre lump over the nape of his neck that appeared three months ago. The lump has not changed in size and remains asymptomatic. His main concern is the appearance of the lump. He has a history of similar lumps on his chest and back. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lump is one centimetre in diameter (Image). It is non-fluctuant but compressible.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most characteristic clinical finding of this lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mobility when pressure is applied to one edge","Pearly rolled border","Tender erythematous dome","Central punctum","Buttonhole depression on palpation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an epidermoid (sebaceous) cyst. These are common benign lesions arising from blocked pilosebaceous units. The presence of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral punctum\u003C/strong\u003E (a small dark opening on the surface) is pathognomonic, representing the blocked duct of the pilosebaceous unit. The cyst contains keratin and lipid debris, giving it its characteristic cheese-like contents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMobility when pressure is applied to one edge\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of lipomas, which are benign fatty tumours found in the subcutaneous tissue. Unlike sebaceous cysts, lipomas lack a punctum and feel soft and doughy on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epearly rolled border\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of basal cell carcinoma, the most common form of skin cancer. These lesions often have a central depression and telangiectasia, features not seen in sebaceous cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etender erythematous dome\u003C/strong\u003E suggests an inflamed lesion such as a furuncle (boil) or infected sebaceous cyst. While sebaceous cysts can become infected, this is not their typical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EButtonhole depression on palpation\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of dermatofibromas and neurofibromas. This finding, also known as the dimple sign, occurs when the lesion is compressed from the sides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of sebaceous cysts depends on symptoms and patient preference. Asymptomatic cysts can be observed, while symptomatic or cosmetically concerning cysts are typically treated with complete surgical excision including the cyst wall to prevent recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A central punctum (dark opening) is the classic clinical finding of a sebaceous cyst, representing the blocked pilosebaceous unit.","Sebaceous cysts are benign, slow-growing lesions that can occur anywhere on the body except palms and soles.","Surgical excision is the definitive treatment for symptomatic or cosmetically concerning sebaceous cysts."],"references":["Epidermoid cyst. Dermnet. https://dermnetnz.org/topics/epidermoid-cyst"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74152"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19447"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21744"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21744"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EchBVg9SoeBl8CqlTW7OYsdSiCT7ZU.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EchBVg9SoeBl8CqlTW7OYsdSiCT7ZU.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74152"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T15:53:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T13:48:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12174"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89993"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-2